/652788/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652788/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-06","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department spent on travel that was not standard class in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","56225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652789","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-12","<p>The Low Pay Commission consulted extensively with a broad range of stakeholders to inform its recommendation for the National Living Wage, including representatives from small and medium-sized businesses. A list of stakeholders consulted is available from page 197 of its report:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572730/LPC_report_autumn_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572730/LPC_report_autumn_2016.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government has accepted the Low Pay Commission’s recommendation for the National Living Wage rate that should apply from April 2017 which is expected to benefit over a million workers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-12T17:09:59.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652789/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652789/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-06","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2016 to Question 55692, for what reasons his Department did not consult small and medium-sized businesses on the effect of a rise in the national living wage on productivity.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","56259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652790","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-14","<p>The Department for International Trade has no unpaid internships.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-14T15:54:33.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652790/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652790/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-06","Department for International Trade: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many unpaid internships there are in his Department.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652791","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-14","<p>The Prime Minister has spoken twice with President-elect Donald Trump to congratulate him on his election victory and discuss how his transition plans are progressing. She highlighted her wish to strengthen bilateral trade and investment with the US as we leave the EU, saying that she looks forward to working with President-elect Donald Trump, building on these ties to ensure the security and prosperity of our nations in the years ahead.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-14T16:04:13.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652791/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652791/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-06","Overseas Trade: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations his Department has received from the transition team of President-elect Donald Trump on future trade relations between the US and the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","56348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652792","Department of Health","false","2016-12-12","<p>The Department is working on ensuring the best outcome for the health and social care system. All policy teams within the Department are involved with this work and assessing the implications of the United Kingdom leaving the European Union on their area. This includes working with NHS England and other arm’s length bodies.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU Exit. The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe, and departments will work together to deliver this.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-12T15:00:02.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652792/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652792/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that the effect on the NHS of the UK leaving the EU is not adverse.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","56352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652793","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-14","<p>We are continuing to work closely with the Department of Health to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will affect health and social care. We will set out as much as is possible as long as it does not undermine our negotiating position.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-14T16:33:14.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652793/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652793/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-06","Health Services and Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2016 to Question 55030, on health services and social services, if he will publish the findings of his Department's work with the Department for Health prior to the submission of notice of intention to leave the EU under Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","56389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652794","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-12","<p>There are no unpaid internships. The Civil Service runs the Summer Diversity Internship Programme, which is a two month placement and is paid. The Civil Service also runs the Early Diversity Internship Programme which is for a week only (and more akin to work experience) – it provides expenses to encourage applications and ensure there is no financial loss.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-12T16:26:53.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652794/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652794/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many unpaid internships there are in his Department.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652954","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-14","<p>The Government issued its most recent assessment of the basic freedoms, the rule of law and democracy in Hong Kong on 12 October in the Foreign Secretary’s Six-Monthly Report to the House. In this we stated that “despite challenges, the UK believes that “One Country, Two Systems” has provided a successful framework for almost two decades, and can continue to do so”.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-14T15:27:37.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652954/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652954/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-06","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what recent assessment they have made of basic freedoms, the rule of law and democracy in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>As a co-signatory of the Sino-British Joint Declaration, the Government is committed to monitoring thoroughly its implementation on an ongoing basis. We do this through the Foreign Secretary's Six Monthly Report to Parliament on Hong Kong. We reaffirmed this approach in the Government's response to the Foreign Affairs Committee report on Hong Kong published in March 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:01:44.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652955/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652955/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-06","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to conduct a comprehensive review of the implementation of the Sino-British Joint Declaration.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652956","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government has no plans to amend the time limit in the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990 on the use of human embryos for research.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T14:56:28.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652956/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652956/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Human Embryo Experiments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to extend the 14-day limit beyond which destructive experiments on human embryos may not take place to 28 days.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-14","<p>We are aware of some limited scientific engagement between UK nationals and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). As per the provisions of UNSCR 2321, such cooperation does not need to be suspended when there is a determination that such activity does not contribute to the DPRK's proliferation, nuclear activities or ballistic missile programmes.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-14T15:28:12.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652957/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-06","North Korea: Sanctions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to United Nations Security Council Resolution 2321, whether any UK organisations or nationals engage in scientific and technical co-operation involving persons or groups officially sponsored by or representing the Democratic People's Republic of Korea; and whether this co-operation will be suspended.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>We are not aware of any UK funding or UK nationals providing teaching and training which could contribute to the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea’s proliferation activities or the development of its nuclear weapons delivery systems.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:02:32.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652958/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-06","North Korea: Sanctions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to United Nations Security Council Resolution 2321, whether any UK funds or United Kingdom nationals provide specialised teaching and training which could contribute to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea’s proliferation activities or the development of nuclear weapons delivery systems, including business and economic management training that may be used to acquire or sell goods used in connection with weapons.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652959","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government welcomes the unanimous adoption of UN Security Council Resolution 2321 and work has begun to ensure that its provisions are fully implemented and enforced within the UK. We continue to have diplomatic relations with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:03:02.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652959/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652959/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-06","North Korea: Sanctions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to United Nations Security Council Resolution 2321, whether they intend to reduce the number of staff at the Embassy of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea in London and what steps they will take to limit the number of bank accounts held by Democratic People's Republic of Korea diplomats stationed in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652960","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-21","<p>Public protection remains our key priority; however, the recent HMIP report rightly highlights concerns around the management of IPP prisoners.</p><p> </p><p>We have set up a new unit within the Ministry of Justice to improve progression for all IPP prisoners and are working with the Parole Board to improve the efficiency of the parole process.</p><p> </p><p>Examples of the initiatives being taken forward as part of the action plan include the need for other Progression Regimes, in addition to the one at HMP Warren Hill; central case reviews led by psychologists and policy specialists of IPP cases where there has been no progression to open conditions despite two or more post tariff parole reviews; and enhanced case management approaches within both NOMS and the Parole Board.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-21T17:43:27.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652960/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652960/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-06","Prison Sentences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Goldie on 22 November (HL Deb, col 1839) concerning the revision of the statutory Parole Board Rules so that parole panels can release imprisonment for public protection prisoners without progressing to an oral hearing, what other measures have been introduced to ensure that prisoners get a thorough assessment<i>.</i>","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652961","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Public Protection Casework Section (PPCS) of the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) is responsible for co-ordinating all information and activity for the parole reviews of indeterminate sentence prisoners. A new discreet unit within PPCS has been established, funded from existing budgets, to augment and enhance the work of PPCS, by focusing on those cases which are particularly complex and where additional support is needed to resolve issues identified during the parole process, without compromising either the integrity of the process or the assessment of risk. Up to 15 full-time equivalent staff will work in the unit.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-01T12:34:43.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652961/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652961/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-06","Prison Sentences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Goldie on 22 November (HL Deb, col 1838) concerning the central unit which is being set up to assess indeterminate sentences, what its remit will be, how many full-time equivalent staff will work for it, what its budget will be, and how it will interact with the National Offender Management Service.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652962","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-23","<p>Restraint should only be used as a last resort, where there is a risk of harm, and where it is absolutely necessary to do so and no other form of intervention is possible or appropriate. Every incident of restraint is reviewed by the establishment. This includes looking at whether any lessons can be learned for the future.</p><p>We will consider publication of the risk assessment for MMPR as part of the Annual MMPR syllabus review.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-23T13:52:27.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652962/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652962/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-06","Young Offenders: Restraint Techniques","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the risk of injury and fatalities resulting from restraint techniques currently used on minors in young offender institutions and secure training centres; whether they will publish the full findings of their assessment; and what steps they are taking to review and modify the use of the relevant techniques.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652963","Attorney General","false","2016-12-20","<p>Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs is the department with principal responsibility for reviewing individual tax affairs. They do not comment on the affairs of identifiable taxpayers.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-20T17:48:28.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652963/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652963/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-12-06","Duchy of Cornwall: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Attorney General or other counsel have reviewed the taxation of the income from the Duchy of Cornwall within the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL3853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652964","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Prison Safety and Reform White Paper (Cmnd 9350), published 3 November 2016, announced the intention to create five small community prisons for women. It said that we will seek to use land adjacent to existing prison sites to get economies of scale, while maintaining the feel of separate institutions that will be important for prisoners’ experiences.</p><p>In line with one of the key recommendations in your review: ‘Women with Particular Vulnerabilities in the Criminal Justice System’, one of our primary objectives is improving closeness to home for women offenders. The creation of these prisons will mean that more women are held closer to their homes and given the support services they need to help them address what are often multiple and complex needs.</p><p>We are currently looking for appropriate sites and will set out further detail on the design and operation of these prisons as part of a wider strategy for female offenders which we will publish next year.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-20T17:44:12.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652964/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652964/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-06","Prisons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to hold men and women prisoners on shared sites.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL3854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652965","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The <em>Challenge on Dementia 2020</em>, published in February 2015, made clear that, by 2020, we expect social care providers to provide appropriate training on dementia to all relevant staff. A copy of the <em>Challenge on Dementia 2020</em> is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Department estimates that more than 100,000 social care workers have already received dementia awareness training. Newly appointed health care assistants and social care support workers, including those providing care and support to people with dementia and their carers, should undergo training as part of the national implementation of the Care Certificate.</p><p> </p><p>Standard 9 of the Care Certificate concerns awareness of mental health, dementia and learning disabilities. In meeting the standard, each worker must show that he or she understands the needs and experiences of people with mental health conditions, dementia or learning disabilities, the importance of promoting their health and wellbeing, the adjustments which may be necessary in delivering their care, and the importance of early detection. They must also prove that they understand the legal context, including mental capacity considerations.</p><p> </p><p>This standard is based in tier 1 of the Dementia Core Skills Education and Training Framework, which focuses on awareness. This tier of knowledge is applicable across the spectrum of health and adult social care services and so is at an appropriate level to inform the Care Certificate’s content.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3856 ; HL3857","2016-12-16T13:13:47.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652965/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652965/answer","Challenge on Dementia 2020.pdf","Challenge on Dementia 2020.pdf","Challenge on Dementia 2020","Challenge on Dementia 2020","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652965/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Dementia: Home Care Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that all homecare workers receive training relating specifically to dementia.","false","Biography information for Baroness Greengross",,"Baroness Greengross","HL3855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652966","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The <em>Challenge on Dementia 2020</em>, published in February 2015, made clear that, by 2020, we expect social care providers to provide appropriate training on dementia to all relevant staff. A copy of the <em>Challenge on Dementia 2020</em> is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Department estimates that more than 100,000 social care workers have already received dementia awareness training. Newly appointed health care assistants and social care support workers, including those providing care and support to people with dementia and their carers, should undergo training as part of the national implementation of the Care Certificate.</p><p> </p><p>Standard 9 of the Care Certificate concerns awareness of mental health, dementia and learning disabilities. In meeting the standard, each worker must show that he or she understands the needs and experiences of people with mental health conditions, dementia or learning disabilities, the importance of promoting their health and wellbeing, the adjustments which may be necessary in delivering their care, and the importance of early detection. They must also prove that they understand the legal context, including mental capacity considerations.</p><p> </p><p>This standard is based in tier 1 of the Dementia Core Skills Education and Training Framework, which focuses on awareness. This tier of knowledge is applicable across the spectrum of health and adult social care services and so is at an appropriate level to inform the Care Certificate’s content.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3855 ; HL3857","2016-12-16T13:13:47.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652966/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652966/answer","Challenge on Dementia 2020.pdf","Challenge on Dementia 2020.pdf","Challenge on Dementia 2020","Challenge on Dementia 2020","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652966/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Dementia: Home Care Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what recent assessment they have made of the level of dementia training provided to homecare workers delivering care to people with dementia.","false","Biography information for Baroness Greengross",,"Baroness Greengross","HL3856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652967","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The <em>Challenge on Dementia 2020</em>, published in February 2015, made clear that, by 2020, we expect social care providers to provide appropriate training on dementia to all relevant staff. A copy of the <em>Challenge on Dementia 2020</em> is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Department estimates that more than 100,000 social care workers have already received dementia awareness training. Newly appointed health care assistants and social care support workers, including those providing care and support to people with dementia and their carers, should undergo training as part of the national implementation of the Care Certificate.</p><p> </p><p>Standard 9 of the Care Certificate concerns awareness of mental health, dementia and learning disabilities. In meeting the standard, each worker must show that he or she understands the needs and experiences of people with mental health conditions, dementia or learning disabilities, the importance of promoting their health and wellbeing, the adjustments which may be necessary in delivering their care, and the importance of early detection. They must also prove that they understand the legal context, including mental capacity considerations.</p><p> </p><p>This standard is based in tier 1 of the Dementia Core Skills Education and Training Framework, which focuses on awareness. This tier of knowledge is applicable across the spectrum of health and adult social care services and so is at an appropriate level to inform the Care Certificate’s content.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3855 ; HL3856","2016-12-16T13:13:47.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652967/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652967/answer","Challenge on Dementia 2020.pdf","Challenge on Dementia 2020.pdf","Challenge on Dementia 2020","Challenge on Dementia 2020","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652967/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Home Care Services: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that people delivering homecare are at Tier 2 within the Care Certificate, equivalent to their NHS counterparts.","false","Biography information for Baroness Greengross",,"Baroness Greengross","HL3857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652968","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-14","<p>In the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 we committed to building eight Anti-Submarine Warfare variant Type 26 Global Combat Ships to replace the current eight Anti-Submarine Warfare variant Type 23 Frigates on a one-for-one basis. My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence announced on 4 November that the steel cut for the first of the Type 26 Global Combat Ships will take place in mid-2017, subject to contract negotiations.</p><p>The Royal Navy remains focused on the target set in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 of 30,450 Royal Navy and Royal Marines personnel in April 2020.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-12-14T16:42:08.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652968/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652968/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Type 23 Frigates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what effect the lack of clarity on the replacement of the Type 23 frigates has had on recruitment to the Royal Navy.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652969","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Government is concerned about the decline of the hedgehog. The reasons for their decline are complex and include agricultural practices (including loss of hedgerows), use of pesticides, reducing availability of food, roads, a lack of available shelter in urban areas, restriction of movement and badgers that predate on hedgehogs and compete for their food.</p><p> </p><p>We support efforts to make our gardens more hedgehog friendly through the creation of hedgehog havens and campaigns encouraging local communities to work together to look out for hedgehogs and make gardens as welcoming as possible.</p><p> </p><p>Working with the British Hedgehog Preservation Society and People’s Trust for Endangered Species, earlier this year the Government published advice for homeowners in the form of five simple steps to make gardens more hedgehog friendly, from letting grassy areas grow wild to providing food and shelter.</p><p> </p><p>More recently, information has been available through social media on how people can help hedgehogs during autumn.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-12-16T13:19:37.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652969/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652969/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-06","Hedgehogs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to raise awareness of the rapid decline in the UK hedgehog population and the reasons for this decline.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652970","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Department has made no formal estimate of the costs of delayed discharge to the National Health Service. However, the Department and NHS Improvement are working together to implement Lord Carter’s recommendations on hospital productivity. The report, <em>Operational productivity and performance in English NHS acute hospitals: Unwarranted variations </em>is attached. As part of this, the two organisations are working with providers to develop a richer dataset around all aspects of the patient pathway, including discharge.</p><p> </p><p>At the same time, the Department continues to work closely with the NHS and local government to help local areas improve transfers out of hospital, share best practice, and reduce unnecessary delays.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Care Act 2014, placed duties on local authorities to facilitate and encourage an effective market of quality providers in their area. The Department has worked with local government and the provider sector to develop guidance to help local authorities with these market shaping duties, a copy of guidance, <em>Adult social care market shaping </em>is attached. The Department also supports the Local Government Association with a programme of sector-led improvement.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-16T13:12:39.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652970/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652970/answer","Operational productivity and performance in English NHS acute hospitals - Unwarranted variations.pdf ; Adult Social Care Market Shaping.pdf","Operational productivity and performance in English NHS acute hospitals - Unwarranted variations.pdf ; Adult Social Care Market Shaping.pdf","Operational productivity  ; Adult social care market shaping","Operational productivity  ; Adult social care market shaping","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652970/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Hospital Beds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the annual cost to the NHS of bed-blocking delays in discharging elderly patients from hospitals because of the lack of adequate social care provision; and what strategy they have to ensure that adequate social care is provided, particularly for the elderly.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652971","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department for Transport does not routinely estimate congestion costs however, as part of the Eddington study in 2006, the Department estimated congestion costs in the most congested Local Authorities and in 2009 published a congestion map as part of the DASTS (Delivering A Sustainable Transport Strategy) City and Regional Networks Data Book showing the most congested towns and cities. The DASTS Databook Annex14 is available at:</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090511045027/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/regional/strategy/databook/" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090511045027/http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/regional/strategy/databook/</a></p><p> </p><p>However, due to both the use of different methodologies, geographies as well as the age of the above analysis, it is not possible to compare the Departments historic analysis of congestion costs with those of INRIX.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-19T12:27:36.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652971/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652971/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-06","Road Traffic","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much they estimate that traffic congestion costs the economy in time wasted (1) in London, and (2) in the 21 most congested UK cities, according to the 2016 INRIX report <i>Europe's Traffic Hotspots: Measuring the Impact of Congestion in Europe</i>.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652972","Department for Education","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Government is committed to raising standards in mathematics to reflect the best practice in the world. In the OECD’s Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA) 2015, 15 year olds in the UK perform at the OECD average in mathematics. Although the UK dropped one place in the PISA rankings for mathematics since 2012 – from 26<sup>th</sup> to 27<sup>th</sup> – five more countries took part in the study and the UK’s score of 494 remained the same from 2012 to 2015.</p><p>We continue to reform our primary and secondary curriculum and standards. The first cohort is due to take the new GCSEs in mathematics next summer. The pupils who sat the 2015 PISA assessment in England were born around the year 2000 and have experienced little of the changes introduced since 2010, and virtually none of the reforms in primary education.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-15T16:14:51.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652972/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652972/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-06","Schools: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the reasons for the UK's static position over the last three years, and in particular its decline in the maths ratings, with reference to the OECD's Programme for International Student Assessment results for 2015.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652973","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-14","<p>Defence procurement projects cover an extensive range of equipment, infrastructure, information services and broad service contracts. Following the Levene reforms, responsibility and budgets for procurement have been delegated in large degree to the Front Line Commands, who use Defence Equipment and Support (DE&amp;S), the Defence Infrastructure Organisation (DIO), as well as Information Systems and Services (ISS), as their principal delivery organisations. The time and cost performance of delegated projects is monitored and controlled by these organisations at a level appropriate to their cost. Only the largest or most contentious projects, such as equipment projects over £400 million or infrastructure projects over £75 million (‘Category A’ Projects), are approved directly by Head Office. This includes review of those projects that overrun on time or cost.</p><p> </p><p>In recent years the National Audit Office (NAO) has provided an independent review of the Ministry of Defence’s delivery performance of the largest procurement projects and presented the findings in an annual publication, the “Major Projects Report” (MPR). These reports include details of the cost, time and quality delivery forecasts for a sample of the largest defence procurement projects that had reached the demonstration and manufacture phases of their project lifecycle – that is to say they had passed the main investment decision point. The reports contain a summary of the projects’ original budgets and their latest forecast costs to completion, enabling individual identification of increases and decreases in cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the combined MPR results for the last three financial years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>MPR15</p></td><td><p>MPR14</p></td><td><p>MPR13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>£ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>In-Year Cost Variation</p></td><td><p>-£247</p></td><td><p>-£397</p></td><td><p>£708</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Cost Variation Since Original Approval</p></td><td><p>£5,552</p></td><td><p>£5,691</p></td><td><p>£6,086</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>[Note: A direct comparison from year-to-year is not possible. Projects enter or exit the MPR population annually following approval or reaching in-service date respectively. Additionally, the scope of projects has also been known to change in response to emergent requirements.]</p><p> </p><p>A more in-depth breakdown on a project-by-project basis, including total cost variance by project, is available in the MPR. Additionally, explanations of the causal factors of the variances can be found for each project in the project summary sheets which accompany the reports.</p><p> </p><p>MPR15:</p><p><a href="https://www.nao.org.uk/report/major-projects-report-2015-and-the-equipment-plan-2015-to-2025/" target="_blank">https://www.nao.org.uk/report/major-projects-report-2015-and-the-equipment-plan-2015-to-2025/</a></p><p>(For the MPR15 Summary Table see Appendix 3, page 42)</p><p> </p><p>MPR14:</p><p><a href="https://www.nao.org.uk/report/major-projects-report-2014-and-the-equipment-plan-2014-to-2024/" target="_blank">https://www.nao.org.uk/report/major-projects-report-2014-and-the-equipment-plan-2014-to-2024/</a></p><p>(for the MPR14 Summary Table see Appendix 2, page 40)</p><p> </p><p>MPR13:</p><p><a href="https://www.nao.org.uk/report/ministry-of-defence-the-major-projects-report-2013/" target="_blank">https://www.nao.org.uk/report/ministry-of-defence-the-major-projects-report-2013/</a></p><p>(For the MPR13 Summary Table see Appendix 3, page 40)</p><p> </p><p>In the first instance, cost overruns must be absorbed by the Front Line Commands by prioritising their projects within overall procurement control totals. How these were apportioned for each of the projects cited in the reports would require further analysis.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-12-14T16:48:38.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652973/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652973/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Defence: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many defence procurement projects have overrun their original budgets over the last three years; at what cost; and who has been responsible for meeting the increased cost.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652974","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Government of the United Kingdom does not possess fully autonomous weapon systems and has no intention of developing them. Such systems are not yet in existence and are not likely to be for many years, if at all. Although a limited number of defensive systems can currently operate in automatic mode, there is always a person involved in setting the parameters of any such mode. As a matter of policy, the UK is clear that the operation of our weapons will always be under human control. This information has been put on record a number of times, in both Parliament and international forums.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-12-13T16:43:27.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652974/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652974/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Autonomous Weapons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what level of human control they consider necessary for compliance with international law in the context of lethal autonomous weapons; and how they will work with other states to define that level of control at the forthcoming Review Conference of the UN Convention on Conventional Weapons.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL3864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652975","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>For courses beginning on 1 August 2017, the main deadline for the majority of full-time undergraduate courses through the University and Colleges’ Admissions Service (UCAS) is 15 January 2017. However, universities can accept applications up until August 2017, and applicants can also apply directly for some part-time and postgraduate courses at specific higher education institutions.</p><p> </p><p>The Department of Health intends to work with ‎the Department for Education, UCAS and other healthcare education bodies to determine the most appropriate point and method following 15 January 2017, to assess available information on applications for pre-registration nursing, midwifery and allied health profession courses.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T14:53:14.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652975/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652975/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Nurses: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 22 November (HL Deb, col 1833), whether an independent assessment of recruitment levels will be carried out in January 2017 once the rate of applications has been calculated.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wheeler",,"Baroness Wheeler","HL3865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652976","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Government has not reassessed plans to replace bursaries with loans to take into account the decision to withdraw from the European Union (EU).</p><p>The Department of Health is working with the Department for Exiting the European Union to ensure that the needs of health and social care providers and those in need of health and social care services are taken into account as we exit from the EU.</p><p>In October 2016, the Department for Education confirmed that EU students will remain eligible to apply for the standard student loan package and this will not change during their course if the Government triggers Brexit during the next few years.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-16T13:15:08.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652976/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652976/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Nurses: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have reassessed their plans to replace bursaries with loans for all nursing students in the light of the potential impact of the decision to withdraw from the UK on the recruitment and retention within the NHS of qualified nurses from other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wheeler",,"Baroness Wheeler","HL3866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652977","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has used the services of a number of consulting firms to help with departmental set-up and planning. The Departmental budget will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-20T15:57:52.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652977/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652977/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-06","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what they anticipate to be the total cost of consultants employed in connection with the UK's negotiations to leave the EU in (1) 2016–17, and (2) 2017–18.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Stamford",,"Lord Davies of Stamford","HL3867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652978","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>I refer the noble Lord to my statement to the House on 31 October 2016, Official Report, Vol. 776.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-19T14:12:13.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652978/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652978/answer","Statement BNR 31.10.16 Nissan Sunderland.pdf","Statement BNR 31.10.16 Nissan Sunderland.pdf","BNR Statement 31st Oct 2016 on Nissan: Sunderland","BNR Statement 31st Oct 2016 on Nissan: Sunderland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652978/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-06","Nissan","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of (1) the maximum, and (2) the likely, total cost of any regional, employment, training, subsidy, grant, incentive payment, or other financial support, which Nissan UK might be entitled to receive over the next (a) five, and (b) 10, years.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Stamford",,"Lord Davies of Stamford","HL3868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652979","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has just over 300 staff, and is growing fast. We are not in a position to give a final total as recruitment is ongoing. Overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are regularly reviewed and we will ensure we are appropriately staffed to deal with the task at hand.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-20T15:55:49.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652979/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652979/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-06","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many civil servants or other public employees they anticipate will need to be recruited in (1) 2016–17, and (2) 2017–18, in connection with the UK's negotiations to leave the EU, and what they expect the total cost of employing them to be in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Stamford",,"Lord Davies of Stamford","HL3869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652980","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>The government is committed to building more integrated communities and widening opportunity. We have spent over £60 million on integration projects since 2010/11, helping to create the conditions for people to live successfully alongside each other.</p><p>This includes funding for community – based tuition to help isolated adults to learn English and the Near Neighbours programme, supporting well over 1,000 small projects bringing people together across faith, social and ethnic boundaries.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government has made clear he will be studying Dame Louise’s findings closely. As part of those considerations, we will look to learn from our existing integration projects. In spring, we will come to the House with our plans for tackling the issues raised by Dame Louise, so that we can continue to build a country that works for everyone.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL3874","2016-12-19T15:34:04.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652980/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652980/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-06","Community Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to encourage people from different ethnic and religious backgrounds to work together on projects and programmes in local communities.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL3870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652982","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>This Government fully supports the provision of more integrated local services.</p><p>The Better Care Fund, for example, is enabling local areas to integrate and transform local health and social care services by 2020. Clinical Commissioning Groups and local authorities pool budgets and agree together how to focus funding to support more person-centred, coordinated care, so people can manage their own health and wellbeing and live independently in their communities for as long as possible, relieving the pressure on acute services. There are 150 Better Care Fund plans, covering each Health and Wellbeing Board area of England. In 2016-17, the Better Care Fund is funding 1,326 schemes across all local authorities with the largest focus for schemes being in developing integrated care solutions.</p><p>The Troubled Families Programme also encourages a different, more effective way for public services to work with families who place a disproportionate burden on them. By doing so, it helps to reduce demand and dependency of complex families on costly reactive public services and deliver better value for the taxpayer. This ‘service transformation’ in early help for complex families, which encourages the integration of local services, is an explicit aim of the programme. On 17th November, guidance for local authorities and their partners was published that sets out the key principles of, and ways to assess, service transformation in early help services for complex families.</p><p>There are also a number of public service reform related commitments in devolution deals, including around accelerating partnership working on the integration of health and social care; innovative employment trials; improving integration of employment support with other local services such as health; greater local influence over public protection including offender management and rehabilitation; and a range of other commitments to transformation and improvement in areas such as children’s services.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-21T12:35:01.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652982/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652982/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-06","Public Sector","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what they are doing to encourage local agencies, both statutory and non-statutory, to provide more integrated local services.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL3871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652983","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>Dame Louise Casey's Review into integration and opportunity published on the 5 December takes account of academic and other research and considers previous community cohesion reports and programmes. The government will be studying her Report carefully and will publish a response in the spring.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T15:34:26.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652983/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652983/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-06","Community Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence there is that practical lessons have been learnt from past research conducted into integration in British communities.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL3872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652984","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>The only comprehensive study, in the last five years, has been Dame Louise Casey's Review into integration and opportunity, published on 5 December 2016.</p><p>A number of Departments will have undertaken studies in support of policy objectives related to integration, however information on the cost of these studies is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T15:28:52.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652984/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652984/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-06","Community Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent over the last five years on studies about integration in British communities and what impact this has had, if any.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL3873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652985","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>The government is committed to building more integrated communities and widening opportunity. We have spent over £60 million on integration projects since 2010/11, helping to create the conditions for people to live successfully alongside each other.</p><p>This includes funding for community – based tuition to help isolated adults to learn English and the Near Neighbours programme, supporting well over 1,000 small projects bringing people together across faith, social and ethnic boundaries.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government has made clear he will be studying Dame Louise’s findings closely. As part of those considerations, we will look to learn from our existing integration projects. In spring, we will come to the House with our plans for tackling the issues raised by Dame Louise, so that we can continue to build a country that works for everyone.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL3870","2016-12-19T15:34:04.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652985/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652985/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-06","Community Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what lessons they have learned from projects with hands-on practical experience of building integrated communities; how they will build on the success of those projects; and what role those projects will play in achieving the changes that are recommended in <i>The Casey Review: a review into opportunity and integration</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL3874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652986","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>Statistics on daily smoking are not routinely gathered. In 2015, the Office of National Statistics Annual Population Survey 2015 showed that 17.6% of 18-19 year old men, 24% of 20-24 year old men, and 27% of 25-29 year old men were current smokers. No data is collected on snus use.</p><p> </p><p>The Tobacco Control plan will provide a framework and call to action for wide ranging future work to further reduce the prevalence of tobacco use.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3876","2016-12-19T14:51:23.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652986/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652986/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Tobacco","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the percentage of men in the UK aged 16 to 29 who (1) smoke cigarettes, and (2) use snus, on a daily basis.","false","Biography information for Viscount Ridley",,"Viscount Ridley","HL3875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652987","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>Statistics on daily smoking are not routinely gathered. In 2015, the Office of National Statistics Annual Population Survey 2015 showed that 17.6% of 18-19 year old men, 24% of 20-24 year old men, and 27% of 25-29 year old men were current smokers. No data is collected on snus use.</p><p> </p><p>The Tobacco Control plan will provide a framework and call to action for wide ranging future work to further reduce the prevalence of tobacco use.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3875","2016-12-19T14:51:23.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652987/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652987/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Tobacco","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to include scientific evidence about the potential of snus as a smoking substitute in their Tobacco Control Plan.","false","Biography information for Viscount Ridley",,"Viscount Ridley","HL3876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652988","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>On 25 November, BEIS published a response to the Management of the Levy Control Framework Lessons Learned Report which set out the actions being taken against each of the recommendations raised in the report including progress to date.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-19T12:31:38.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652988/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652988/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-06","Energy: Prices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they plan to take to implement the recommendations of the Kelly report <i>Management of the Levy Control Framework: Lessons Learned Report (2015)</i>.","false","Biography information for Viscount Ridley",,"Viscount Ridley","HL3877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652989","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department is currently considering this issue, along with the other recommendations and actions arising from the Public Accounts Committee hearing on the Levy Control Framework that took place on 30 November. A response to the Committee will be submitted in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-19T12:32:59.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652989/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652989/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-06","Energy: Prices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will resume publication of the estimated impacts of energy and climate policies on energy prices and bills, as part of its commitment to increased transparency, as recommended in the Kelly report <i>Management of the Levy Control Framework: Lessons Learned Report (2015)</i>.","false","Biography information for Viscount Ridley",,"Viscount Ridley","HL3878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652990","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Levy Control Framework, including progress against the recommendations in the Kelly report, is considered as part of the normal course of business for the Department’s Audit and Risk Assurance Committee. This committee is chaired by a Non-Executive Member of the Department’s Board.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-19T12:33:42.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652990/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652990/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-06","Energy: Prices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, and if so when, the non-executive directors of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy will be asked to review implementation of the Kelly report <i>Management of the Levy Control Framework: Lessons Learned Report (2015)</i>.","false","Biography information for Viscount Ridley",,"Viscount Ridley","HL3879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652991","Home Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>Progress on resettlement in each local authority is indicated in quarterly immigration statistics. The last set of statistics, published on 1 December 2016 showed that 4,162 Syrians were relocated to the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement (VPR) scheme between October 2015 and September 2016 and sets out how many were located in each local authority. The figures include those Syrians resettled with a community sponsor during this period.</p><p>The refugees that we are bringing to the United Kingdom are very vulnerable people. Our prime concern is their safety and protection as they arrive in this country. We want to protect their privacy and ensure their recovery and integration, as they rebuild their lives in safe and secure surroundings, among supportive communities in the UK. We will, therefore, not be providing a running commentary on numbers that have been resettled with a community sponsor.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-20T17:29:26.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652991/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652991/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-06","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many refugees have been resettled through the Syrian vulnerable person resettlement scheme and community sponsorship scheme in each region of the UK.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Durham",,"The Lord Bishop of Durham","HL3880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652992","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>NHS Digital publishes information on the number of cancelled outpatient appointments as part of Outpatient Hospital Episode Statistics which are published annually. Not all appointments are consultant-led and it is not possible to separately identify the number of cancelled consultant-led appointments.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015-16, 7.6 million outpatient appointments were cancelled by hospitals, representing 6.8% of all appointments.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-16T13:14:26.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652992/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652992/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","NHS: Consultants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 16 November (HL2985), if the information about the number of NHS consultant appointments cancelled is not held in the format requested, in what format that information is held.","false","Biography information for Lord Lisvane",,"Lord Lisvane","HL3881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652993","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-19","<p>The purpose of THINK! is to reduce the number of people killed and seriously injured on our roads. Campaign priorities are determined on this basis. They are thoroughly researched and evidenced using casualty data, road safety literature and audience insight.</p><p> </p><p>Decades of road safety communications and sixteen years of THINK! campaign activity have demonstrated the importance of focusing our interventions in areas where we think communications can make the greatest difference to safe road user behaviour.</p><p> </p><p>We continually evaluate priorities for the THINK! campaign, reviewing casualty statistics on an ongoing basis to ensure that our campaigns have the greatest impact on road safety. We currently have no plans to develop a campaign that encourages drivers to get their eyes tested.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-19T12:29:59.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652993/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652993/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-06","Driving: Eyesight","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Think Bike Think Biker and Tiredness Kills campaigns, what plans they have to launch a campaign to encourage drivers to get their eyes tested.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL3882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652994","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-19","<p>All personal-injury accidents on the public highway that are attended by a police officer should be recorded and reported to the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>The set of information collected for each accident includes a list of factors which, in the judgement of the police officer, contributed to the accident. One of these factors is ‘uncorrected, defective eyesight’. Police officers attending accidents should record this feature in all cases where poor vision was a factor.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-19T12:34:14.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652994/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652994/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-06","Roads: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to ensure that all road traffic accident reports include, as a matter of routine, an assessment of whether poor vision was a factor.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL3883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652995","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government has committed to providing an additional 5,000 doctors working in general practice by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Medical assistants do not form part of this commitment.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T14:59:42.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652995/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652995/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Doctors: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many of the promised 5,000 extra doctors will be medical assistant posts.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL3884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652996","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) is a crime and it is child abuse. We will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls.</p><p>Mandatory reporting of FGM came into force in October 2015 and requires regulated health and social care professionals and teachers to report known cases in under 18s to the police. Figures are not collated centrally. However, we continue to engage with the police, professional bodies and wider stakeholders to monitor its implementation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3886 ; HL3887","2016-12-21T12:39:24.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652996/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652996/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-06","Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the statutory mandatory reporting duty in relation to female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL3885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652997","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) is a crime and it is child abuse. We will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls.</p><p>Mandatory reporting of FGM came into force in October 2015 and requires regulated health and social care professionals and teachers to report known cases in under 18s to the police. Figures are not collated centrally. However, we continue to engage with the police, professional bodies and wider stakeholders to monitor its implementation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3885 ; HL3887","2016-12-21T12:39:24.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652997/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652997/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-06","Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reports have been made by teachers, social workers and health professionals, so far, to the police regarding known cases of female genital mutilation involving victims under the age of 18.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL3886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652998","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) is a crime and it is child abuse. We will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls.</p><p>Mandatory reporting of FGM came into force in October 2015 and requires regulated health and social care professionals and teachers to report known cases in under 18s to the police. Figures are not collated centrally. However, we continue to engage with the police, professional bodies and wider stakeholders to monitor its implementation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3885 ; HL3886","2016-12-21T12:39:24.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652998/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652998/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-06","Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will require cross-government working in order to ensure a cohesive approach is adopted in addressing female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL3887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652999","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The UK is working closely with the Nigerian government to eradicate the abusive practice of female genital mutilation in Nigeria.</p><p>Nigeria is one of 17 countries targeted by the Department for International Development's £35 million programme working towards ending Female Genital Mutilation/Cutting (FGM/C) in Africa.</p><p>The programme focuses on three areas: building the evidence base for tackling FGM, working with the UN on challenging social norms and with governments on policy measures, as well as support for Africa-led campaigns.</p><p>Our broader development programme in Nigeria also includes initiatives that tackle violence against women and girls. This includes UK support for implementation of the Violence Against Persons (Prohibition) Act, which criminalizes female genital mutilation.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:03:36.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652999/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652999/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-06","Nigeria: Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Nigeria about the issue of female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL3888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653000","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>National Health Service commissioners actively use Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) data to plan FGM services locally.</p><p> </p><p>For example, in London, NHS England is piloting the triangulation of data with local population prevalence and police data, to evaluate the multi-agency approach to their FGM prevention work, and they will explore national roll-out of this approach in the new year.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, NHS England is working with police and social care partners to overlay the information from the NHS Digital reports with other FGM information sources to create a more extensive picture of FGM. This in turn will build a broader understanding of FGM, and how best to use this combined information to commission appropriate services for girls and women affected.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T14:52:03.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653000/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653000/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what analysis they have made of the Female Genital Mutilation Enhanced Data in relation to the support provided by the NHS to women and girls who have had or who are at risk of female genital mutilation.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL3889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653001","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>We attempt to deliver the best possible care for patients within the resources available, including by adapting to the latest innovations.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3893","2016-12-20T15:26:32.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653001/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653001/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","NHS: Innovation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why new innovations developed by Medtech are not adopted by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653002","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T14:52:26.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653002/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653002/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","NHS: Innovation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many innovations invested by companies such as Medtech have been taken up abroad due to lack of NHS adoption.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653003","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T14:58:54.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653003/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653003/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","NHS: Innovation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many innovations by companies such as Medtech, which have received funding from taxpayer-funded grants, have been adopted by the UK and how many have not.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653004","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>We attempt to deliver the best possible care for patients within the resources available, including by adapting to the latest innovations.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3890","2016-12-20T15:26:32.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653004/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653004/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-06","NHS: Innovation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why innovations that might save the NHS considerable amounts of money, have passed safety checks, and have proven to be beneficial to patients, have not been taken up by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653005","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>This information is not held in the format requested and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-12-13T16:43:46.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653005/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653005/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Armed Forces: Officers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many one-star ranks and above in the UK armed forces attended a state school beyond the age of 16.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL3894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653006","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Civil Service recruits on the basis of merit and assesses on the basis of evidence supplied by the candidate. This is in line with fair and open competition rules as laid out in the recruitment principles upheld by the Civil Service Commission.</p><p>Gender identity is not used as part of the sifting process of job applications within the Civil Service. Candidates are asked this information for diversity monitoring purposes only.</p><p>The Civil Service aims to become the most inclusive employer in the UK, with the Talent Action Plan focussing on removing barriers for those from underrepresented groups.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-19T17:30:28.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653006/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653006/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-06","Civil Servants: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they use responses to questions about gender identity in some civil service job applications to determine the best-qualified candidate, and if such a question is not answered how detrimental this would be to the application.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL3895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653007","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary ratio of their highest to lowest paid employees. The Office for National Statistics do publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organisation. These ratios are published annually as part of <em>Civil Service Statistics </em>and can be found attached.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-19T17:40:06.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653007/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653007/answer","Civil Service statistics 2016.pdf","Civil Service statistics 2016.pdf","Civil Service Statistics 2016","Civil Service Statistics 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/653007/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-06","Civil Servants: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the ratio between the salary of a civil servant on the lowest grade to the Permanent Secretary in each of the Government departments represented in the Cabinet.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL3896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656592","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>The UK is one of four nations leading NATO’s enhanced Forward Presence, providing the Framework Battalion in Estonia and a reconnaissance squadron in Poland, joining the US-led force there. These defensive but combat-capable forces deliver reassurance to our Allies and deterrence against Russian belligerence. Next year we are deploying Typhoon aircraft to Romania to deliver Southern Air Policing, and will lead NATO’s Very High Readiness Joint Task Force.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","907791","2016-12-12T16:40:11.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656592/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656592/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to deter Russian expansion in eastern Europe; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","907790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656593","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>Ministers regularly raise the two per cent commitment during discussions with our NATO Allies.</p><p>For example, the Secretary of State was in Brussels last month and he reminded his counterparts that Britain is committed to spending two per cent of our GDP on defence every year of this decade and encouraged them to meet the commitment they all made at the Wales Summit in 2014.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-12-12T17:33:21.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656593/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656593/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Defence: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his NATO counterparts on the commitment to spend at least two per cent of GDP on defence.","false","Biography information for Claire Perry","Devizes","Claire Perry","907784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656594","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>The first UK Poseidon P-8A aircraft will be delivered in 2019, when it will be subject to trials in America. It is anticipated that this aircraft will begin to operate from RAF Lossiemouth in 2020.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-12-12T17:32:54.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656594/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656594/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the timetable is for the Boeing P-8 Poseidon aircraft to be brought into operational service.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","907788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656595","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave earlier today to the hon. Member for Mid Worcestershire (Nigel Huddleston).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-12-12T17:32:30.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656595/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656595/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Defence Equipment: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to encourage innovation by defence suppliers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","907793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656596","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>Funding has been approved for the refurbishment of the five barrack blocks at RAF Odiham in the poorest condition. This work is due to commence in April 2017 with a completion date in financial year 2021-22.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-12-12T16:41:31.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656596/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656596/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","RAF Odiham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he plans to take to improve accommodation at RAF Odiham in 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","907787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656597","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>The Ministry of Defence continues to work with partners across Government and the United Nations to explore options to get aid into Aleppo. The Government also used its contacts with Armed Opposition Groups to persuade them to accept the UN’s 4-point plan unconditionally. The regime needs to do likewise but is refusing to do so because they are using starvation and siege as weapons of war.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-12-12T16:40:50.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656597/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656597/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Syria: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department is providing to the UN and other aid agencies to deliver humanitarian aid to people in Aleppo.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","907789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656598","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-12","<p>The UK is one of four nations leading NATO’s enhanced Forward Presence, providing the Framework Battalion in Estonia and a reconnaissance squadron in Poland, joining the US-led force there. These defensive but combat-capable forces deliver reassurance to our Allies and deterrence against Russian belligerence. Next year we are deploying Typhoon aircraft to Romania to deliver Southern Air Policing, and will lead NATO’s Very High Readiness Joint Task Force.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","907790","2016-12-12T16:40:11.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656598/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/656598/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-06","Eastern Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the UK is taking to defend NATO's eastern flank.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Gower","Gower","Byron Davies","907791"
