 than 5</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>Less than 5</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>Less than 5</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 (mid year for births)</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>Less than 5</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 (mid year for treatments)</p></td><td><p>34</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority</p><p> </p><p>*Part year data not available.</p><p> </p><p>This corrects my earlier answer.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T12:25:08.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651809/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651809/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 8 November (HL2858 and HL2861), why the data provided by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) in table 3 of the first of those answers detail that no live births resulted from frozen donated oocytes between 2008–14, whereas the data provided by the HFEA included in the second of those answers detail that in relation to treatments that took place prior to 30 June 2014, 72 patients aged 35 and over using donated frozen oocytes had a live birth.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651810","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department does not hold a record of how many letters have been sent out in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not reported to the police any incidents of suspected violation of the Act and Regulations relating to Registered Medical Practitioners terminating a pregnancy who have not given notice in form HSA4 to the Chief Medical Officer (CMO) within 14 days of the termination. Where HSA4 forms have been submitted late, the Department is working closely with doctors, hospitals/clinics and the Royal College of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. The Department is helping to identify issues with HSA4 submission to support doctors, hospitals and clinics in ensuring that protocols and processes exist internally to ensure the transmission of HSA4 forms meets the legislative framework. The Department currently receives around two-thirds of HSA4 forms electronically and is actively encouraging more doctors to submit HSA4 forms online. Receiving HSA4 forms online reduces the risk of late submission of forms to the CMO.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3793","2016-12-19T12:30:55.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651810/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651810/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 1 December (HL3358), how many letters were sent to registered medical practitioners by officials to remind them of their legal obligation to report terminations of pregnancy within 14 days, in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651811","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department does not hold a record of how many letters have been sent out in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not reported to the police any incidents of suspected violation of the Act and Regulations relating to Registered Medical Practitioners terminating a pregnancy who have not given notice in form HSA4 to the Chief Medical Officer (CMO) within 14 days of the termination. Where HSA4 forms have been submitted late, the Department is working closely with doctors, hospitals/clinics and the Royal College of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. The Department is helping to identify issues with HSA4 submission to support doctors, hospitals and clinics in ensuring that protocols and processes exist internally to ensure the transmission of HSA4 forms meets the legislative framework. The Department currently receives around two-thirds of HSA4 forms electronically and is actively encouraging more doctors to submit HSA4 forms online. Receiving HSA4 forms online reduces the risk of late submission of forms to the CMO.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3792","2016-12-19T12:30:55.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651811/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651811/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 1 December (HL3359), how many registered medical practitioners have been reported for suspected violations of the Abortion Regulations 1991, having failed to report terminations within the 14-day period, in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651812","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The phrase “wilful non-compliance” stems from Section 2(3) of the Abortion Act 1967 which provides that any person who wilfully contravenes or wilfully fails to comply with the requirements of regulations under subsection (1) of this section shall be liable on summary conviction to a fine without limit.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T12:19:40.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651812/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651812/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 1 December (HL3359), from what authority, legislative or common law, the phrase "wilful non-compliance" derives with respect to the Abortion Regulations 1991.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651813","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-14","<p>Our commitment to Hong Kong as a co-signatory of the Joint Declaration is as strong as ever. On 2 December the Parliamentary Undersecretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Mr Sharma) visited Hong Kong and spoke publicly about the importance of Hong Kong's rights and freedoms. The Government's most recent assessment of the basic freedoms and the rule of law in Hong Kong is set out in the Foreign Secretary's Six-Monthly Report to the House of 12 October. In this we stated that&quot; despite challenges, the UK believes that &quot;One Country, Two Systems&quot; has provided a successful framework for almost two decades, and can continue to do so&quot;. The full report can be found online - (https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/six-monthly-report-to-parliament-on-hong-kong-january-june-2016).</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-14T16:51:17.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651813/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651813/answer","Six-Monthly_Report_on_Hong_Kong_-_1_January_-_30_June_2016.pdf","Six-Monthly_Report_on_Hong_Kong_-_1_January_-_30_June_2016.pdf","Foreign Secretary's six monthly report - Hong Kong","Foreign Secretary's six monthly report - Hong Kong","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651813/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Hong Kong: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to fulfil their legal obligations under the Sino-British Joint Declaration to monitor and speak out for basic freedoms and the rule of law in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651814","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Hong Kong courts reached a decision on the cases of Yau Wai-ching and Sixtus Leung on the basis of Hong Kong's legal framework. We respect this decision.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-13T16:08:41.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651814/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651814/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the court ruling in Hong Kong disqualifying two elected legislators from the Legislative Council.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651815","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-19","<p>Using actual self-assessment data, HM Revenue and Customs estimate that only 1 in 5 landlords will pay more tax as a result of this measure. Given that only a small proportion of the housing market is affected by these changes, the Government does not expect them to have a large impact on rent levels.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Incorporated businesses will continue to receive relief at the corporate tax rate. However, the rate of relief (currently 20%) is not more generous than the rate of income tax relief once these changes are fully in place by 2020-21.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL3798","2016-12-19T15:37:06.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651815/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651815/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Landlords: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to take steps to ensure that limited companies are not better placed than other landlords in relation to the taxation of profits engendered by letting residential properties.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651816","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-19","<p>Using actual self-assessment data, HM Revenue and Customs estimate that only 1 in 5 landlords will pay more tax as a result of this measure. Given that only a small proportion of the housing market is affected by these changes, the Government does not expect them to have a large impact on rent levels.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Incorporated businesses will continue to receive relief at the corporate tax rate. However, the rate of relief (currently 20%) is not more generous than the rate of income tax relief once these changes are fully in place by 2020-21.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL3797","2016-12-19T15:37:06.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651816/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651816/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Landlords: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to introduce plans to prevent landlords of residential properties from recouping the cost of changes to the taxation of rents of such properties which will come into force next year; and if so, how.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651817","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>Officials are continuing their work on the implementation of the Housing &amp; Planning Act 2016. The process to implement secondary legislation will be on-going throughout 2017, as will the process to consult and publish on specific sections of the Act.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T15:24:59.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651817/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651817/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the estimated timetable for the publication of (1) responses to the consultations on provisions contained in the Housing and Planning Act 2016, and (2) the secondary legislation required to implement those provisions.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651818","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-08","<p>I can confirm that certain provisions of these Acts are still extant and that the Government has no plans to repeal these Acts.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-08T12:27:07.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651818/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651818/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-05","Ports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Docks and Harbours Act 1966 and the Harbour (Loans) Act 1972 continue to have any legislative effect; and if not, whether they have any plans to repeal those Acts.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL3800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651819","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>Over 893,000 additional homes have been delivered in England since April 2010.Full information including a breakdown by new build, conversion, change of use and other changes is available (attached) at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-net-supply-of-housing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-net-supply-of-housing</a></p><p>Figures show an estimated increase of 2.1438 million in the population of England between mid-2010 and mid-2015. Full information, including historical population estimates for the UK and England, is published by the Office for National Statistics, and available (attached) at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T15:26:47.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651819/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651819/answer","HL3801 Copy of LiveTable_120.xls ; Population of England - HL3801 data4829405668430689475.xls","HL3801 Copy of LiveTable_120.xls ; Population of England - HL3801 data4829405668430689475.xls","Housing supply ; Population of England","Housing supply ; Population of England","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651819/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","Housing Completions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many new housing completions have occurred since 2010; and what is the estimated increase in the UK's population during that period.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL3801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651820","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-12","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the statement I made to the House on this matter on 31 October 2016, Official Report<em>, </em>Volume 776.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-12T15:01:42.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651820/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651820/answer","Nissan_ Sunderland - Hansard Online (P).pdf","Nissan_ Sunderland - Hansard Online (P).pdf","Hansard - Nissan statement","Hansard - Nissan statement","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651820/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-05","Nissan","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, before submitting notice of intention to leave the EU under Article 50 of the Treaty of Lisbon, they will publish the terms of the support and assurances given to Nissan relating to the continuation of their operations in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL3802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651821","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>The role of the police in managing demonstrations is to preserve the peace, to uphold the law and to prevent the commission of offences. Police tactics and decisions on how to achieve these objectives are a matter for the independent operational judgement of chief officers of police.</p><p>The Metropolitan Police Service has a proportionate policing plan in place to maintain public order in the vicinity of the Supreme Court for the duration of the hearing of the Article 50 case.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-12T12:10:15.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651821/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-05","Supreme Court: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are satisfied that, in co-operation with the Metropolitan Police, they have made adequate arrangements to safeguard public order and security in the vicinity of the Supreme Court when members of the Court are giving attention to, and announcing their judgement upon, the issues relating to the notification of the intention to leave the EU under Article 50 of the Treaty of Lisbon.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL3803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651822","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-19","<p>There are no plans to amend the Oath.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-19T16:37:49.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651822/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651822/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-05","Lord Chancellor","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to amend the Oath of Office of the Lord Chancellor to "defend the independence of the judiciary" as contained in the Constitutional Reform Act 2005.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL3804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651823","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>The UK intends to deploy up to 400 troops to the UN peacekeeping mission in South Sudan (UNMISS) of whom, approximately 6%, are expected to be female. This would be double the UN average, with women making up about 3% of UN peacekeepers worldwide. In addition, the UK has four male personnel at the UN mission's headquarters in Juba, including the Chief of Staff.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-12-13T16:44:12.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651823/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651823/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-05","South Sudan: Peacekeeping Operations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the number of (1) women, and (2) men, who will be deployed in the UK peacekeeping office in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL3805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651824","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>There are now over 40 Gender Focal Points (GFPs) within the ranks of the UK Armed Forces, including in the Ministry of Defence, four of whom are awaiting deployment to the UN peacekeeping mission in South Sudan.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-12-13T16:44:28.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651824/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651824/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-05","Ministry of Defence: Gender","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many gender focal points exist in (1) the UK's armed forces, (2) the Ministry of Defence, and (3) the UK's peacekeeping force in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL3806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651825","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-13","<p>The nutrition position paper is being updated to reflect the priorities set out in the Multilateral and Bilateral Development Reviews. It is anticipated that we will publish this paper in spring 2017.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-12-13T17:43:14.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651825/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651825/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-05","Developing Countries: Nutrition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to publish the Department for International Development's global nutrition position paper.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL3807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651826","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-13","<p>DFID Malawi is designing a new health and nutrition approach.</p><p>DFID has supported integrated health and nutrition services in Pakistan since 2013 and in India since 2007. This will remain a focus for DFID Pakistan, whilst DFID India’s support for health and nutrition ended in March 2016.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-12-13T17:42:56.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651826/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651826/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-05","Developing Countries: Nutrition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to integrate UK-funded health and nutrition programmes in (1) Malawi, (2) Pakistan, and (3) India.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL3808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651827","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-12","<p>In Q2 2016 household debt relative to income fell to 142%, down from its peak of 160 percent in Q1 2008. Unsecured debt as a proportion of household income was 39 per cent in Q2 2016, down from a peak of 44 percent in Q1 2007. The government recognises that there is more to be done to help those in problem debt. The Money Advice Service (MAS), an arms-length body of the Treasury coordinates the provision of publicly-funded free to client debt advice. In 2015-2016 MAS had a £75m budget and in that financial year made 300,000 money guidance sessions and 380,000 debt advice sessions available to consumers<strong>. </strong>In October 2016 the government announced plans to bring publicly-funded debt advice, money guidance, and pensions guidance together in a single guidance body, responsible for providing impartial, free-to-client guidance and for promoting financial capability.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, we have created the independent Financial Policy Committee within the Bank of England, to ensure emerging risks and vulnerabilities across the financial system as a whole, including in relation to household debt, are identified, monitored and effectively addressed.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-12-12T15:11:50.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651827/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651827/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Debts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to address the level of household debt, the rate at which it is increasing, and the multiple it represents of annual household income.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL3809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651828","Department of Health","false","2016-12-15","<p>Adult social care is largely delivered through an independent sector of care provider organisations that operate in a competitive market. As with any market, some providers enter and exit, which is an important mechanism for driving up quality and effectiveness. Market exits are regular occurrences and are handled effectively by local government.</p><p> </p><p>It is of course vital that vulnerable people with care needs do not have their services interrupted if their care provider failed financially and services stop. The Care Act 2014 introduced new duties on local authorities and the Care Quality Commission (CQC) to protect and reassure people with care needs, their families and friends. The Act places a duty on all local authorities in England to temporarily step in and make sure all people in their area continue to have their needs met, regardless of who pays for their care. Recognising that local authorities might struggle if a significant provider were to fail, the CQC has a new function to oversee and monitor the financial sustainability of the largest and most difficult to replace providers. The oversight function provides an early warning to relevant local authorities in the event that one of these providers is likely to fail and their services cease.</p><p> </p><p>Four Seasons Health Care is one of the providers that because of their size, is part of the CQC’s Market Oversight Scheme. CQC continues to monitor the finances of all of the providers in the scheme. Government has no powers to require a private company that is acting lawfully to change its financial approach.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Act 2014 also places new duties on local authorities to promote their local market to ensure all service users have a choice of high quality services available.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-15T12:52:11.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651828/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651828/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","Four Seasons Health Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the debt levels of Four Seasons Health Care; whether they have any plans to intervene to protect the interests of patients; and whether they are able to require the company's private equity owner to invest new equity.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL3810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651829","Home Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>Money laundering investigations are conducted by law enforcement agencies with access to the powers in the Proceeds of Crime Act, such as the National Crime Agency, the Serious Fraud Office, and the police. All of these law enforcement agencies are operationally independent of the Government.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-20T12:46:59.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651829/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651829/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-05","Sovereign Wealth Funds: Malaysia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are investigating matters relating to Malaysia’s state investment fund, 1MDB, and the role played by Goldman Sachs International Limited and its officers past and present.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL3811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651830","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government has no plans to regulate mortgages at high multiples of income.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has granted the Financial Policy Committee (FPC) powers of direction with regard to owner-occupied mortgages. The Government recently brought forward secondary legislation to grant the FPC powers of direction with regard to buy to let mortgages as well. This instrument has been debated and approved in this House and the other place.</p><p> </p><p>The FPC is a policy committee of the independent Bank of England. It is for the Committee to decide if, when and how to use its powers.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-12-19T15:43:31.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651830/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651830/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Mortgages","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to regulate further the granting of residential mortgages at high multiples of income.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL3812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651831","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) requests that all members declare any personal or business interests which the public might reasonably think could influence their judgement as part of the activities undertaken for the UK NSC on the conflict of interest form and declaration.</p><p> </p><p>The conflict of interest form further requests for the member to include any personal direct and indirect interests, including close family members and others living in the same household. The form is consistent with those of other scientific advisory committees and upholds the seven principles of public life – the Nolan principles. Members are able to express any changes in situations at any time and are directed to withdraw from any discussions where they feel they cannot act impartially.</p><p> </p><p>Termination of membership from the UK NSC may arise where the Chair takes in good belief that the member has acted dishonestly or under duress to influence a recommendation.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T12:18:19.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651831/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651831/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","National Screening Committee","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 22 November (HL3125), whether the public disclosure of a relevant interest is sufficient in all cases relating to appointments to the UK National Screening Committee; and if not, what types of interest would prevent an individual from being appointed or from continuing to serve on the Committee.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL3813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651832","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>Non-invasive prenatal testing for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes is an additional test to be offered as part of the current NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme, and as it does not fundamentally alter the choices already available to women, we consider that there will be no impact on race, age, disability, gender reassignment sex or sexual orientation, religion or belief, marriage and civil partnership or pregnancy and maternity for the purposes of the Public Sector Equality Duty under the Equality Act 2010. The Department also considers that the programme is compliant with the Equality Act because it is not discriminatory and, with regard to the three elements of the Public Sector Equality Duty in s.149 of that Act, it has a neutral impact.</p><p> </p><p>The Department considers that adding this optional alternative procedure to the current screening programme is compliant with the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, as the test is intended to allow pregnant women to identify possible abnormalities in a foetus with more accuracy and in a less intrusive way than is possible through other screening procedures. Pregnant women will then be able to make a better informed choice in the light of the screening results.</p><p> </p><p>All relevant equality duties will be further considered by Public Health England during the evaluative roll-out.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T12:19:14.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651832/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651832/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-05","Pregnancy: Screening","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton 21 November (HL3063) indicating that no equality impact assessment was conducted prior to the decision to introduce non-invasive prenatal testing on the NHS, what is the basis for the statement that they are satisfied that the screening programme is compliant with the Department’s obligations under the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities and that the programme is compliant with any obligations under the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL3814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651833","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>While we have not raised this issue, we will continue to make clear our concerns over East Jerusalem to the Israeli authorities and the Municipality of Jerusalem, both bilaterally and in co-operation with our EU partners. We view any attempts to change the facts on the ground as a serious provocation likely to raise tensions and cause unnecessary suffering to ordinary Palestinians, as well as being harmful to the peace process and in contravention of international law.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T15:54:37.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651833/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651833/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Israeli Settlements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding reports of Israeli settlers illegally obtaining Palestinian-owned land in East Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651834","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>We continue to call on the governments of Israel and Egypt to show maximum flexibility in opening the crossings into Gaza to help facilitate travel in and out of Gaza. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv most recently raised the issue of movement and access with the Israeli authorities on 5 December. We also remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of movement between the West Bank and East Jerusalem. We continue to work closely with EU partners to call on Israel to ease access these restrictions. Our Embassy in Tel Aviv regularly lobbies the Israeli authorities on the issue of movement and access.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T15:55:26.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651834/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651834/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel concerning restrictions on the movement of Palestinian civilians in the Gaza Strip and the West Bank, including occupied East Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651835","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>We raised a number of allegations with the Israeli authorities on 14 November, and have urged for a thorough investigation and for any perpetrators to be brought to justice.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T15:55:50.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651835/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651835/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel concerning reports of Palestinians being injured by Israeli forces and settlers while harvesting olives.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651837","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>Whilst we have not raised this specific issue with the Israeli authorities, the UK regularly raises its concerns about confiscations with the Government of Israel.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T15:56:11.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651837/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651837/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel in response to the report by the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs that Israeli officials seized an electric generator and a metal-cutting machine belonging to an aid organization near Nablus.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651838","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-13","<p>The UK is concerned by this kind of disruption of humanitarian assistance to Palestinian communities. We regularly raise our concerns about demolitions with the Government of Israel, and continue to call on the Government of Israel at the highest levels to ease restrictions on humanitarian access across the Occupied Palestinian Territories.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-12-13T17:42:01.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651838/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651838/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-05","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel in the light of the statement issued on 10 November by the UN Coordinator for Humanitarian Aid and Development Activities condemning the Israeli authorities’ obstruction of humanitarian assistance for to Palestinian communities.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651839","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government condemns all acts of violence by extremist settlers. Settler violence is an abhorrent phenomenon which must be tackled firmly. We have repeatedly raised with the Israeli authorities our concerns about incidents of settler violence and intimidation, including the importance of bringing the extremist settlers responsible to justice.</p><p>We raised a number of allegations concerning violence against Palestinians during the olive harvest with the Israeli authorities on 14 November, and have urged for a thorough investigation and for any perpetrators to be brought to justice.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T15:57:16.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651839/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651839/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Israeli Settlements: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding the reports alleging physical assault by Israeli settlers on Palestinians living in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651840","Department for Education","false","2016-12-12","<p>This is a matter for the Office of Qualifications and Examinations Regulation (Ofqual) and I have asked its Chief Regulator, Sally Collier, to write directly to the Noble Peer.</p><p>A copy of her reply will be placed in the House Libraries.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-12T16:26:09.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651840/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651840/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-05","Ofqual: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the source of funding for Ofqual; whether it levies fees and charges; and if so, (1) under what authority, (2) against whom, and (3) what mechanisms there are for challenging the level of those fees and charges.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL3821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651841","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>Ofcom is currently funded through fees from industry for regulating broadcasting and communications networks and from grant in aid from government. The Digital Economy Bill contains a provision to change Ofcom’s funding so that it will be entirely self-funded, only receiving grant-in-aid for delivery of specific government programmes</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Under the Communications Act 2003 (sections 38 - 39 and 347) the Broadcasting Act 1990 (sections 4 and 87), the Broadcasting Act 1996 (sections 4 and 43) and the Postal Services Act 2011 (section 43), Ofcom is required to raise income from each of the sectors it regulates, such that it covers the costs to be incurred by Ofcom in regulating that sector.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom currently raises its funds from:</p><ol><li>TV and Radio broadcasters;</li><li>Providers of on-demand programme services;</li><li>Electronic communication network and services providers;</li><li>The Postal Universal Service Provider and</li><li>DCMS grant in aid</li></ol><p> </p><p>Ofcom imposes its fees in accordance with its published Statement of Charging Principles. Whilst there is no statutory mechanism for challenging Ofcom’s fees, before making or revising its Statement of Charging Principles Ofcom must first consult those people who, in its opinion, are likely to be affected by the principles contained in that document. Ofcom also responds to stakeholders queries on the fees and charges set.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-12-15T13:01:46.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651841/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651841/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-05","Ofcom: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the source of funding for Ofcom; whether it levies fees and charges; and if so, (1) under what authority, (2) against whom, and (3) what mechanisms there are for challenging the level of those fees and charges.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL3822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651842","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>Ofgem’s annual budget is approved by Parliament but its main funding comes from the licence fee it is able to levy on licence holders under the Gas Act 1986 and the Electricity Act 1989.</p><p> </p><p>Through its Forward Work Programme, Ofgem agrees its annual licence fee (and any amendments to this) in consultation with licence holders, and publishes its cost recovery principles on its website. The basic principle is that costs are recovered from network licensees in line with the proportion of gas or electricity customers that are directly connected to their respective networks. Ofgem also charges cost-reflective fees to consider applications for new licences or licence variations.</p><p> </p><p>It also receives some funding directly from Government for the administration of environmental schemes.</p><p> </p><p>There is no formal mechanism to appeal against the level of the licence fee, although Ofgem is subject to Parliamentary scrutiny and must abide by the principles for Fees, Charges and Levies set out in Managing Public Money:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/454191/Managing_Public_Money_AA_v2_-jan15.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/454191/Managing_Public_Money_AA_v2_-jan15.pdf</a></p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-15T16:47:25.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651842/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651842/answer","HL3823 - Managing_Public_Money.pdf","HL3823 - Managing_Public_Money.pdf","Managing Public Money","Managing Public Money","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651842/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-05","Ofgem: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the source of funding for Ofgem; whether it levies fees and charges; and if so, (1) under what authority, (2) against whom, and (3) what mechanisms there are for challenging the level of those fees and charges.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL3823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651843","Department for Education","false","2016-12-13","<p>There are two legislative restrictions in place. “University” is a sensitive word under company law<sup>[1]</sup>, which means permission from the Secretary of State under the Companies Act 2006, following a non-objection letter from the Department for Education, is required before it can be used in a business or company name. Also, under section 39 of the Teaching and Higher Education Act 1998, an institution cannot offer educational services under a name which includes “university” unless authorised by Act or Royal Charter or approved by the Privy Counsel.</p><p>[1] Company, Limited Liability Partnerships and Business Names (Sensitive Words and Expressions) Regulations 2014 (S.I. 2014/3140)</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-12-13T14:27:06.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651843/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651843/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-05","Universities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there are any legal restrictions on the ability of an organisation or institution operating in England to use the term "university" as part of its title.","true","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL3824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651844","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-12","<p>Analysis has shown that enough spectrum has been made available for PMSE to meet all demand. It is, therefore, up to industry to decide how they work within the constraints of the allocated spectrum and to plan their events accordingly.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-12-12T14:42:56.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651844/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651844/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-05","Radio Frequencies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 17 November (HL3043), whether a contingency plan for the Programme Making and Special Events sector exists; if not, when they will start to draft a contingency plan; and which stakeholders will be consulted as the contingency plan is compiled.","false","Biography information for Baroness Benjamin",,"Baroness Benjamin","HL3825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651845","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-12","<p>At the current time, other European countries believe there will be enough capacity within the 470-694MHz band to meet the requirements of the Programme Making &amp; Special Events industry so, other than the UK, there are currently no plans in other countries to allocate alternative spectrum for PMSE.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-12-12T14:43:34.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651845/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651845/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-05","Radio Frequencies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 17 November (HL3046), what has been the reaction of the French, German and Dutch regulators to the representations made by Ofcom; and what further discussions they will be having with other European countries to ensure that future spectrum allocations do not have unintended consequences for the Programme Making and Special Events sector.","false","Biography information for Baroness Benjamin",,"Baroness Benjamin","HL3826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651846","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>We have some concerns that the rights of third-country nationals working in the Kingdom are not always fully respected, mainly because existing legislation is not always rigorously enforced. Where we have concerns about the legislative or regulatory protection of migrant workers, we raise these with Governments.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T15:58:39.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651846/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651846/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Saudi Arabia: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Goldie on 9 November (HL Deb, col 1146), what assessment they have made of the legislative protections afforded to migrant workers in Saudi Arabia; whether they have raised concerns regarding these protections with the government of Saudi Arabia; and if so, what was the outcome.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651847","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>As members of the Global Coalition, the UK and Turkey regularly discuss operations in Syria. The majority of the area in northern Syria currently held by Turkish-backed opposition was previously dominated by Daesh. We are not aware of any recent clashes between the Turkish-backed opposition and the People's Protection Units in Afrin Canton. We call on all parties to work alongside the Global Coalition to achieve our shared objective of defeating Daesh.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:00:05.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651847/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651847/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 1 December, what discussions they have had with the government of Turkey about the area of Northern Syria now occupied by the Turkish army; what proportion of the occupied area was previously controlled by Daesh; whether Afrin Canton is now under Turkish attack; and whether Turkey gives advance warning of its plans to the United States and British commanders.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651848","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>In 2014 the Prime Minister’s cross-party Holocaust Commission undertook a nationwide public consultation, receiving more than 2500 responses to its Call for Evidence. This resulted in the Commission recommending the creation of a new National Memorial to the Holocaust and an accompanying Learning Centre to be prominently located in Central London.</p><p>Following an extensive search across central London, which included discussions within Government and with property owners and developers across Central London; invitations to respond to a site specification; and a thorough search by property agents CBRE, Victoria Tower Gardens was identified as a possible location for the Memorial.</p><p>The Memorial will serve as a reminder of the depths of depravity that a seemingly enlightened society can plunge to if it abandons its democratic values, and the importance of constant vigilance in protecting these values. There could be no more powerful or appropriate location to make such a statement than next to Parliament. As a result, and following consultation with Westminster City Council and The Royal Parks, the UK Holocaust Memorial Foundation, which advises DCLG in this matter, recommended that the Memorial be located in Victoria Tower Gardens. This was announced by the Government in January 2016.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL3830","2016-12-19T15:24:26.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651848/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651848/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","World War II: Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consultation, if any, and what reasons, led to the announcement in January by the former Prime Minister, David Cameron, that a National Holocaust Memorial should be sited in Victoria Tower Gardens.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651849","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>In 2014 the Prime Minister’s cross-party Holocaust Commission undertook a nationwide public consultation, receiving more than 2500 responses to its Call for Evidence. This resulted in the Commission recommending the creation of a new National Memorial to the Holocaust and an accompanying Learning Centre to be prominently located in Central London.</p><p>Following an extensive search across central London, which included discussions within Government and with property owners and developers across Central London; invitations to respond to a site specification; and a thorough search by property agents CBRE, Victoria Tower Gardens was identified as a possible location for the Memorial.</p><p>The Memorial will serve as a reminder of the depths of depravity that a seemingly enlightened society can plunge to if it abandons its democratic values, and the importance of constant vigilance in protecting these values. There could be no more powerful or appropriate location to make such a statement than next to Parliament. As a result, and following consultation with Westminster City Council and The Royal Parks, the UK Holocaust Memorial Foundation, which advises DCLG in this matter, recommended that the Memorial be located in Victoria Tower Gardens. This was announced by the Government in January 2016.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL3829","2016-12-19T15:24:26.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651849/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651849/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","World War II: Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to meet the authorities of both Houses of Parliament, Westminster City Council, the Thorney Island Society and other local residents and interested parties, to discuss the implications of a National Holocaust Memorial in Victoria Tower Gardens.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651850","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>In January 2015, Government announced that it was accepting all the recommendations of the Prime Minister’s Holocaust Commission. In doing so, Government also committed £50 million as its contribution to total project costs.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T15:27:55.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651850/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651850/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","World War II: Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to contribute financially to a National Holocaust Memorial, wherever that might be sited, with or without an attached visitor and learning centre; and if so, to what extent.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651851","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The UK has raised the detention and treatment of Kurdish politicians with the Turkish authorities at Ministerial level, and will continue to do so where we have human rights concerns.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:00:36.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651851/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651851/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Ahmet Türk","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to make representations to the government of Turkey about the imprisonment in Silivri Prison of Ahmet Turk, a co-founder of the HDP party.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651852","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>We are grateful to the local pilots for the work they have done on options for the future of statutory notices, which are important tools to ensure that the public are kept informed of decisions and changes that affect them as individuals and communities. We are considering the reports of the pilot programmes carefully.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T15:27:14.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651852/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651852/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","Local Government: Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the 24 local pilot programmes on statutory notices; and what plans they have to make statutory notices more cost-effective.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL3833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651853","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>Since 2013, local authorities have been required to set aside some of their business rates as &quot;provisions&quot; to meet the cost of future business rates appeals. The timing of the settlement of those appeals, therefore, is less relevant to local authorities' financial planning than their ability to estimate the scale of future appeal losses. We have agreed with local government that the difficulty of estimating future appeal losses, together with the way in which the business rates retention scheme deals with those losses, can impact adversely on authorities' financial planning and finances. In designing the new 100 per cent business rates retention scheme, therefore, we are looking again, in collaboration with local government representatives, at the way in which the new system should deal with appeal losses and aim to bring forward proposals shortly.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T16:53:26.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651853/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651853/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","Non-domestic Rates: Appeals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of unresolved business rates appeals on financial planning in local government.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL3834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651854","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The words of the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) in Parliament on 11 November reflected overwhelming concern at Russia’s actions in Syria, which are contributing to the appalling humanitarian situation. The UK will continue to urge Russia to work with the international community to establish a credible ceasefire, and begin working for a political transition that represents the only long-term solution. There is of course a well-established right for citizens in the UK to conduct peaceful demonstrations on issues of concern. The UK is scrupulous about fully meeting and respecting its obligations under the Vienna Convention. We discuss these shared obligations with the Russian Government on a regular basis.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-19T16:01:14.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651854/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651854/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-05","Embassies: Demonstrations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 28 November (HL3232) concerning the Foreign Secretary’s remarks encouraging demonstrations outside the Russian Embassy, whether it is their policy that such demonstrations should not be encouraged; and, if so, whether they have given assurances to that effect to the government of Russia.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651855","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-19T17:23:41.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651855/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651855/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-05","Charities: Grants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen on 2 December (HLWS306) concerning Government grant standards, what was the total amount of donations made by Government departments and the NHS to charities in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651856","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-14","The process is as set out in Article 50. The precise timing and organisation of the negotiations will be a matter for discussion. It will be in everyone's interests to get a good deal agreed as quickly as possible.",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-14T16:50:40.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651856/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651856/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-05","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by the Prime Minister on 30 November (HC Deb, col 1518) that there would be two years of negotiations on the UK exiting the EU, whether it is their intention for the UK to leave the EU at the earliest possible point, notwithstanding the two year period set out under Article 50 of the Treaty of Lisbon.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651857","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-14","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. The outcome of the exit negotiations will determine what arrangements apply in relation to EU legislation in future once the UK has left the EU.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-14T16:50:16.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651857/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651857/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-05","EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, following notice to leave the EU under Article 50 of the Treaty of Lisbon, they intend to continue to implement new EU Directives.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651858","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-19","<p>We are focussed on securing the best possible deal for the United Kingdom as we leave the European Union. Once we have left, it will be for the United Kingdom to decide how taxpayers' money is spent.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-19T16:02:05.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651858/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651858/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-05","EU Budget: Contributions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by the Secretary of State for Exiting the EU on 1 December (HC Deb, col 1648), whether they are considering making continuing financial contributions to the EU budget following the UK’s exit from the EU in order to continue trading with EU countries; and, if so, why.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651859","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-14","<p>The Government estimated in 2013 that overseas students (EU and non-EU) in higher education in the UK contributed £9.7 billion to the UK economy in 2011, through tuition fees and living expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education will publish a new estimate of the total value of education exports to the UK economy shortly, based on data from 2014. This will include updated estimates on the financial contribution of overseas students.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-12-14T16:49:04.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651859/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651859/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the financial contribution of overseas students to the UK economy.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Winchester",,"The Lord Bishop of Winchester","HL3840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651860","Department for Education","false","2016-12-13","<p>The table below shows that the number of Non-EU students entering UK Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) over the last five years. Entry data for 2015/16 and 2016/17 are currently unavailable.</p><p> </p><p>First year enrolments domiciled in Non-EU countries prior to study</p><p>UK HEIs</p><p>Academic Years 2012/13 to 2016/17</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>171,900</p></td><td><p>179,400</p></td><td><p>174,300</p></td><td><p>Not Available</p></td><td><p>Not Available</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) Student Record</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-12-13T14:28:47.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651860/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651860/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-05","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of overseas students coming to study in the UK over the last five years, and the impact of any decline in that number on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Winchester",,"The Lord Bishop of Winchester","HL3841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651861","Department for Education","false","2016-12-13","<p>In Autumn 2015, as part of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement, the following estimates were published, based on forecasts by English universities. These forecasts only include English Higher Education Institutions and do not separate out Home and EU students.</p><p>English Higher Education Institutions</p><p>Forecasts of student numbers</p><p>Academic Year 2015/16 – 2019/20</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>2019/20</p></td><td><p>Total growth</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Home and EU students (FTE)</p></td><td><p>1,300,000</p></td><td><p>1,340,000</p></td><td><p>1,370,000</p></td><td><p>1,400,000</p></td><td><p>1,440,000</p></td><td><p>130,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-EU students (FTE)</p></td><td><p>260,000</p></td><td><p>280,000</p></td><td><p>300,000</p></td><td><p>310,000</p></td><td><p>320,000</p></td><td><p>55,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: English universities’ forecasts, Higher Education Funding Council of England (HEFCE). Figures may not sum due to rounding.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-12-13T14:28:05.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651861/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651861/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-05","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of overseas students, excluding EU students, coming to study in the UK over the next five years.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Winchester",,"The Lord Bishop of Winchester","HL3842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651862","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>We are making good progress following Parliamentary agreement on the 4<sup>th</sup> and 5<sup>th</sup> Carbon Budgets. We are engaging with businesses, industry, and stakeholders, and we are looking forward to publishing a plan in early 2017.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-19T16:52:35.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651862/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/651862/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-05","Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made on setting out their policies and proposals to meet their emissions targets due to be included in their emission reduction plan; and when they will publish them.","false","Biography information for Lord Stunell",,"Lord Stunell","HL3843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652260","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) is working with the Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra) - who own the Government Buying Standards (GBS) for vehicle procurement - on an update that will promote the purchase of safer and cleaner vehicles where appropriate. New standards are expected by 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-13T11:01:19.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652260/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652260/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-05","Motor Vehicles: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the British Road Safety Statement, published in December 2015, what progress has been made on the revision of government buying guidelines to promote the uptake of procuring safer vehicles.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","56093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652261","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The high-level vehicle data that is held centrally does not include the safety specific standard equipment or the optional safety related extras that may have been added. Consequently, we are unable to provide the information required.</p><p>The Crown Commercial Service is committed to supporting the British Road Safety Statement and has recently put in place a Vehicle Telematics Framework to support public sector fleets in addressing driver behaviour and adopting safer driving policies.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-12-08T09:32:27.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652261/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652261/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-05","Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many safer vehicles have been procured by each government department since the adoption of the Road Safety Statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","56094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652262","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>GOV.UK Verify is already accepting registrations. Citizens have been able to verify their identities in order to access government services since 14 October 2014. Since then, GOV.UK Verify has been used more than 1 million times, with 945,000 identity accounts verified so far.</p><p>Work on the two main local authority trials - relating to residents’ parking permit services applications and older people’s concessionary travel - started in October and November 2016 respectively. Both trials are currently in their user research and design phases; the build and testing of prototypes will start in February 2017. GOV.UK Verify expects the first local authority councils to connect to its platform in summer 2017.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","56147","2016-12-08T09:15:32.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652262/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652262/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-05","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people have verified their identity using the gov.uk Verify system since its inception.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652263","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>GOV.UK Verify is already accepting registrations. Citizens have been able to verify their identities in order to access government services since 14 October 2014. Since then, GOV.UK Verify has been used more than 1 million times, with 945,000 identity accounts verified so far.</p><p>Work on the two main local authority trials - relating to residents’ parking permit services applications and older people’s concessionary travel - started in October and November 2016 respectively. Both trials are currently in their user research and design phases; the build and testing of prototypes will start in February 2017. GOV.UK Verify expects the first local authority councils to connect to its platform in summer 2017.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","56146","2016-12-08T09:15:32.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652263/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652263/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-05","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he expects the gov.uk Verify to be in use by the 19 local authorities participating in proposed local government trials of that service.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652264","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-12","<p>The allegations relating to the actions of Royal Bank of Scotland’s Global Restructuring Group are being investigated by the Financial Conduct Authority. In November this year the FCA released the summary findings of the skilled person’s report it commissioned to investigate these allegations. The FCA is an independent, non-governmental body and the review is solely within its remit.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-12-12T14:40:57.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652264/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652264/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on the reported dash for cash policy relating to senior managers at the Royal Bank of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","56156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652265","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-12","<p>The government has established a National Productivity Investment Fund (NPIF) to provide £23bn of additional spending between 2017/18 and 2021/22. Every penny spent by the UK government is explicitly earmarked for areas that are critical to boosting productivity: economic infrastructure (transport and digital communications), Research and Development (R&amp;D), and housing.</p><p> </p><p>Further details about specifically how and where this money will be invested will be set out by the relevant departments and agencies in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Where spending on measures within the NPIF does not extend to Scotland, Wales or Northern Ireland, the devolved administrations will receive funding through the Barnett formula in the usual way.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-12T14:52:53.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652265/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652265/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","National Productivity Investment Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 1 December 2016 to Question 55190, what estimate he has made of the proportion of spending from the National Productivity Investment Fund to be allocated to projects outside London; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","56178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652266","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-12","<p>This information is not held centrally within HM Treasury. The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-12-12T14:37:36.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652266/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652266/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Treasury: Personnel Management","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people employed in human resources roles in his Department have (a) prior experience and (b) qualifications in human resources.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652267","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-12","<p>No decision has been taken on whether the UK remains in the EU single market or the EU customs union. The relationship we build with the EU will be bespoke to the UK. The government is considering carefully the impact of all the available options.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-12T14:45:12.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652267/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652267/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-05","Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the change required in the (a) cost and (b) number of personnel required for customs administration if the UK departs the (i) EU single market and (ii) EU customs union.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","56122"
