"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652405","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-13","<p>Homelessness acceptances remain less than half the 2003-4 peak, but one person without a home is still one too many. That is why we have protected £315 million for local authority homelessness prevention funding, and secured £149 million central government funding in this Parliament.</p><p>We have a strong homelessness safety net, but we want to go further by putting prevention at the heart of our approach to tackling homelessness. That is why we are supporting Bob Blackman MP’s Private Members’ Bill. The Homelessness Reduction Bill will significantly reform England’s homelessness legislation, ensuring that more people get the help they need earlier to prevent them from becoming homeless in the first place.</p><p>Homelessness statistics are recorded at a local authority level. Statistics for each of the last five years on statutory homelessness acceptances, homelessness prevention and relief and rough sleeping by each local authority in England are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-12-13T15:51:46.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652405/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652405/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-05","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the levels of homelessness were in (a) Liverpool, Walton constituency, (b) Merseyside and (c) England in each year from 2010 to 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","56136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652406","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Prime Minister is clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government. We intend to bring forward a social justice green paper in the new year.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-08T11:41:24.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652406/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652406/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-05","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to publish the delayed Life Chances Strategy or a replacement in 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","56144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652407","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-13","<p>There are no unpaid internships. The Civil Service runs the Summer Diversity Internship Programme, which is a two month placement and is paid. The Civil Service also runs the Early Diversity Internship Programme which is for a week only (and more akin to work experience) – it provides expenses to encourage applications and ensure there is no financial loss.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-13T16:06:08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652407/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/652407/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-05","Department for Work and Pensions: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many unpaid internships there are in his Department.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56132"
